<div id="p73" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#4&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=73#p73">2008-03-06 12:10:41</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89602">arvid</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Administrator</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; This proposal addresses the use case where peers are either on an IPv4 network running Teredo [1] or peers are on an IPv6 network with an IPv4 tunnel interface.<br /><br />What about peers connected to the IPv6 internet directly?</p></div></blockquote><p>What about them? If they also have an IPv4 address they can specify it.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; announce response<br /><br />When should peers6 be returned? Always? Just on IPv6 announces?</p></div></blockquote><p>When an IPv6 address is specified or when the announce arrived on an IPv6 interface.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>Is there an option to not return peers(4)?</p></div></blockquote><p>Not in the current draft. Would there be a significant benefit?<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>Should peers with both a v4 and a v6 address be returned once? Or twice?</p></div></blockquote><p>Twice, once for each endpoint address.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; The tracker SHOULD perform a NAT check on the IPv6 endpoint.<br /><br />Like I've said before, I think this is infeasible, but should also be a MUST. This is a contradiction, so I think this design won't work.<br /><br />It's infeasible because it adds considerable overhead to an announce. Especially when that overhead was previously minimized by the UDP tracker protocol. Trackers that handle 1000+ announces per second will (probably) have trouble doing 1000+ NAT checks per second.<br />It should be a MUST to prevent address spoofing.<br />It also assumes the client knows it's own IPv6 (or IPv4) address, which might not be the case when NAT is used.</p></div></blockquote><p>Trackers only perform a NAT check once per peer. Only if you have a 100% turnover of peers within the announce interval will your scenario be valid. In that scenario bittorrent won't work very well anyway.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>An option would be to do two announces, one over IPv4 and one over IPv6.<br />It might be possible to partly merge those two announces when a UDP tracker protocol is used to reduce the overhead as far as possible.</p></div></blockquote><p>The main drawbacks I see with that are:<br /><br />1) You assume that every DNS server supports IPv6 (which is not the case currently)<br />2) There will be extra load on the tracker.<br /><br />I expect Teredo to become a significant share of the bittorrent traffic, given that it does hole punching. I think it makes sense to assume that the number of Teredo users will be much more significant than actual IPv6 users.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
