<div id="p75" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#5&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=75#p75">2008-03-06 14:55:39</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=35956">ghazel</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>BitTorrent Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; This proposal addresses the use case where peers are either on an IPv4 network running Teredo [1] or peers are on an IPv6 network with an IPv4 tunnel interface.<br /><br />What about peers connected to the IPv6 internet directly?</p></div></blockquote><p>This proposal should function for that case as well.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; announce response<br /><br />When should peers6 be returned? Always? Just on IPv6 announces?<br />Is there an option to not return peers(4)?<br />Should peers with both a v4 and a v6 address be returned once? Or twice?</p></div></blockquote><p>The assumption was that v4 peers would be returned if ipv4= is present or the transport is over v4, and v6 peers would be returned if ipv6= is present or the transport is over v6. So, a v6 transport with no v4 parameter would be a case where the tracker can return just &quot;peers6&quot;.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; The tracker SHOULD perform a NAT check on the IPv6 endpoint.<br /><br />Like I've said before, I think this is infeasible, but should also be a MUST. This is a contradiction, so I think this design won't work.<br /><br />It's infeasible because it adds considerable overhead to an announce. Trackers that handle 1000+ announces per second will (probably) have trouble doing 1000+ NAT checks per second.<br />It should be a MUST to prevent address spoofing.<br />It also assumes the client knows it's own IPv6 (or IPv4) address, which might not be the case when NAT is used.</p></div></blockquote><p>If the tracker does not NAT check the endpoint, it is welcome to place it in the peer list, with the knowledge that it could be fake. It's also welcome to drop the address if it does not NAT check it. Our custom tracker does not have significant trouble issueing NAT checks - they do not need to be performed for every request, only new peers.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>An option would be to do two announces, one over IPv4 and one over IPv6.</p></div></blockquote><p>With uTorrent, the tracker could be placed in the torrent file twice, once at the v4 address and once at the v6 address, in different tiers.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>Especially when that overhead was previously minimized by the UDP tracker protocol. <br />It might be possible to partly merge those two announces when a UDP tracker protocol is used to reduce the overhead as far as possible.</p></div></blockquote><p>UDP tracker extension is a topic for another BEP, and should not conflict with this BEP.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
