			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>&gt; What about them? If they also have an IPv4 address they can specify it.<br /><br />I know, but it's weird that your proposal doesn't claim to address that use case.<br /><br />&gt; Not in the current draft. Would there be a significant benefit?<br /><br />When the peer has no IPv4 at all.<br /><br />&gt; Twice, once for each endpoint address.<br /><br />Why is that? When both peers have IPv6, it seems like a waste to also return the IPv4 address.<br /><br />&gt; Only if you have a 100% turnover of peers within the announce interval will your scenario be valid.<br /><br />Or after tracker restart, but that could be fixed with queueing.<br /><br />&gt; In that scenario bittorrent won't work very well anyway.<br /><br />Why would it not work?<br /><br />&gt; 1) You assume that every DNS server supports IPv6 (which is not the case currently)<br /><br />Hmm, true.<br /><br />&gt; 2) There will be extra load on the tracker.<br /><br />Maybe true. <br /><br />&gt; I expect Teredo to become a significant share of the bittorrent traffic, given that it does hole punching. I think it makes sense to assume that the number of Teredo users will be much more significant than actual IPv6 users.<br /><br />Short-term, yes. I hope not long-term. Doesn't Teredo require the ISP to set up a relay server?<br /><br />&gt; If the tracker does not NAT check the endpoint, it is welcome to place it in the peer list, with the knowledge that it could be fake.<br /><br />I don't think it's a good idea to be happy with that kind of behaviour.<br /><br />&gt; It's also welcome to drop the address if it does not NAT check it. <br /><br />But that decreases the effectiveness (of using IPv6).<br /><br />How do you do the quoting BTW?</p>
				</div>
