<div id="p102" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#14&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=102#p102">2008-03-19 16:23:45</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89643">Himaatin</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>only some of the biggest trackers out there: the pirate bay, denis.stalker and anything else that runs on opentracker.</p></div></blockquote><p>It's not the best solution, just because a few popular sites are using it.<br /><br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>Note that a tracker does not have to run on an ipv6 interface to be ipv6 capable.</p></div></blockquote><p>And that's where I beg to differ: How is an IPv4-only tracker supposed to serve IPv6-only clients, or to check IPv6-entries for connectivity?<br />IMHO a tracker shall not track a protocol it isn't able to use. In other words: IPv4-only trackers should only track IPv4 clients, as IPv6-only trackers shall only track IPv6-clients (which both is possible with the original concept, BTW). Only for trackers that speak both protocols themselves there is a need to think about how to proceed with the (dual) clients.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
