<div id="p104" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#16&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=104#p104">2008-03-20 01:27:07</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89643">Himaatin</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>Why not? What is the inherent benefit of using a single key with complicated semantics over two separate keys with very simple semantics?</p></div></blockquote><p>The difference IS the semantics.<br />The term &quot;peers&quot; says nothing about a protocol, it just defines, that the content is a peer.<br />Limiting &quot;peers&quot; to IPv4 only, would be the same, as saying that the term &quot;vehicle&quot; from now on may only be used to denominate bicycles, but not for cars or any other kind of vehicle.<br /><br />Besides: It's much more intuitional. In a &quot;normal&quot; environment (with no compact-response), the &quot;peers&quot;-key already contains IPv6-peers (as well as IPv4-peers and DNS-names), so why should it be different for compact?<br />(It would be a completely different situation, if a compact-response wouldn't contain a &quot;peers&quot;-key in the first place and instead used &quot;peers_ipv4&quot; and &quot;peers_ipv6&quot;)<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>It uses Teredo for instance</p></div></blockquote><p>Teredo is just another way of using IPv6.<br />A tracker, that uses Teredo IS using IPv6 and therefore not an IPv4-only tracker anymore.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
		</div>
	</div>
