<div id="p113" class="blockpost roweven">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#24&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=113#p113">2008-03-22 02:02:14</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89643">Himaatin</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>The 8472 wrote:</h4><p>Who said that ipv6-only was the only relevant scenario? It's also necessary to enable hybrid v4/v6 clients to find each other, even when another network component (the tracker in that case) is still v4.</p></div></blockquote><p>Why? If all clients are able to perfectly communicate via IPv4, why should they use IPv6?<br />But even if there is a reason: If they want to use IPv6, while the tracker can't use it, they should care about exchanging their addresses by themselves.<br />There is no need for an IPv4-tracker to track IPv6-clients (or the other way around).<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>This will become an important scenario in the next few years, long before ipv6-only will be relevant.</p></div></blockquote><p>What makes you think, that an IPv6-only scenario isn't relevant? What about&nbsp; the asians, that don't get IPv4 anymore?<br /><br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><h4>Olaf van der Spek wrote:</h4><p>&gt; there should be no NAT with ipv6... only firewalls.<br /><br />What's the difference?</p></div></blockquote><p>Technically those are completely different things. But since usually NAT comes with some sort of firewall it doesn't make much difference from a tracker's point of view. I think the issue is, that the connectivity check shouldn't have been called &quot;NAT check&quot; in the first place... that's why semantics are important.</p>
					<p class="postedit"><em>Last edited by Himaatin (2008-03-22 02:03:10)</em></p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
