<div id="p114" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#25&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=114#p114">2008-03-22 09:25:35</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=89618">The 8472</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Azureus Developer</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Discussion of BEP 7: IPv6 Tracker Extension</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>What about&nbsp; the asians, that don't get IPv4 anymore?</p></div></blockquote><p>Which, again, will not happen for several years. Earliest projected date of v4 depletion is 2011 to my knowledge. And btw, i did not say that ipv6-only is not relevant in general, i'm only saying that v4+v6 will be here much sooner than the latter.<br /><br /></p><blockquote><div class="incqbox"><p>Why? If all clients are able to perfectly communicate via IPv4, why should they use IPv6?</p></div></blockquote><p>Because the µTorrent guys for example are going to use teredo to connect nodes for NAT circumvention and to evade traffic shaping (although i think the latter won't work). This means the nodes will be v4 in reality but speak v6 via tunneling, so they'll contact the trackers via v4 for example.<br /><br />As i said, v4-trackers handing out v6-addresses is a real scenario and it already works... so why are we still discussing this?</p>
				</div>
				<div class="postsignature"><hr />Az dev</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
